#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:3
msgid "Contributing to Pygments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:5
msgid ""
"Thanks for your interest in contributing! Please read the following "
"guidelines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:10
msgid "Licensing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:12
msgid ""
"The code is distributed under the BSD 2-clause license. Contributors making "
"pull requests must agree that they are able and willing to put their "
"contributions under that license."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:18
msgid "General contribution checklist"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:20
msgid ""
"Check the documentation for how to write :doc:`a new lexer "
"<lexerdevelopment>`, :doc:`a new formatter <formatterdevelopment>`, :doc:`a "
"new style <styledevelopment>` or :doc:`a new filter <filterdevelopment>`. If "
"adding a lexer, please make sure you have read :ref:`lexer-pitfalls`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:28
msgid "Run the test suite with ``tox``, and ensure it passes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:30
msgid ""
"Make sure to add a test for your new functionality, and where applicable, "
"write documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:33
msgid ""
"Use the standard importing convention: ``from token import Punctuation``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:36
msgid "Goals & non-goals of Pygments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:39
msgid "Python support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:41
msgid ""
"Pygments supports all supported Python versions as per the `Python "
"Developer's Guide`_. Additionally, the default Python version of the latest "
"stable version of RHEL, Ubuntu LTS, and Debian are supported, even if "
"they're officially EOL. Supporting other end-of-life versions is a non-goal "
"of Pygments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:51
msgid "Validation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:53
msgid ""
"Pygments does not attempt to validate the input. Accepting code that is not "
"legal for a given language is acceptable if it simplifies the codebase and "
"does not result in surprising behavior. For instance, in C89, accepting `//` "
"based comments would be fine because de-facto all compilers supported it, "
"and having a separate lexer for it would not be worth it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:61
msgid "Language support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/contributing.rst:63
msgid ""
"While we strive for the broadest language support possible, we can't support "
"every programming language on the planet. Our minimum bar is fairly low, but "
"to avoid pet projects and other one-off languages, we expect any language "
"that is proposed for inclusion to have a reasonably sized community around "
"it. If you need a syntax highlighter for your in-house programming language "
"or the brand new language project you kicked off, consider writing a :doc:"
"`plugin <plugins>` until it gains enough popularity."
msgstr ""
